{"parse":{"title":"Mantle (clothing)","pageid":22131141,"revid":796624748,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the garment. For the shield used in medieval warfare, see <a href=\"/wiki/Mantlet\" title=\"Mantlet\">Mantlet</a>. For the garment worn by Catholic priests, see <a href=\"/wiki/Mantelletta\" title=\"Mantelletta\">Mantelletta</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1871_dolman.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/1871_dolman.jpg/220px-1871_dolman.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"193\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/1871_dolman.jpg/330px-1871_dolman.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/1871_dolman.jpg/440px-1871_dolman.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"760\" data-file-height=\"668\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1871_dolman.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Woman's <a href=\"/wiki/Dolman\" title=\"Dolman\">dolman</a> mantle, front &amp; back views. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Harper%27s_Bazaar\" title=\"Harper&#39;s Bazaar\">Harper's Bazaar</a></i>, November 1871</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>mantle</b> (from <i>mantellum</i>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Latin\" title=\"Latin\">Latin</a> term for a <a href=\"/wiki/Cloak\" title=\"Cloak\">cloak</a>) is a type of loose <a href=\"/wiki/Garment\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Garment\">garment</a> usually worn over indoor <a href=\"/wiki/Clothing\" title=\"Clothing\">clothing</a> to serve the same purpose as an <a href=\"/wiki/Overcoat\" title=\"Overcoat\">overcoat</a>. Technically, the term describes a long, loose <a href=\"/wiki/Cape\" title=\"Cape\">cape</a>-like cloak worn from the 12th to the 16th century by both sexes, although by the 19th century, it was used to describe any loose-fitting, shaped outer garment similar to a cape.<sup id=\"cite_ref-fdf_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fdf-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  For example, the <a href=\"/wiki/Dolman\" title=\"Dolman\">dolman</a>, a 19th-century cape-like woman's garment with partial sleeves is often described as a mantle.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Mantelets\">Mantelets</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mantle_(clothing)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Mantelets\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:172px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1895_mantelet.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/1895_mantelet.jpg/170px-1895_mantelet.jpg\" width=\"170\" height=\"279\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6e/1895_mantelet.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"213\" data-file-height=\"350\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1895_mantelet.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Mantelet, French, 1895</div></div></div>\n<p>A variation on the mantle is the <b>mantelet</b> (also spelled <b>mantelot</b> and <b>mantlet</b>), typically describing a short version of the mantle. The term appears as early as 1386, in \"<a href=\"/wiki/The_Knight%27s_Tale\" title=\"The Knight&#39;s Tale\">The Knight's Tale</a>\" by <a href=\"/wiki/Geoffrey_Chaucer\" title=\"Geoffrey Chaucer\">Geoffrey Chaucer</a>. In the 18th century, a mantelet was a woman's short cloak, and in the early 19th century, it was an ornamental <a href=\"/wiki/Scarf\" title=\"Scarf\">scarf</a> that crossed over the chest and tied behind, usually made of <a href=\"/wiki/Fur\" title=\"Fur\">fur</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Lace\" title=\"Lace\">lace</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-fdf_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fdf-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> By the end of the 19th century, a mantelet was a woman's shoulder cape with elongated ends in front, sometimes held in position by a belt at the waist.<sup id=\"cite_ref-fdf_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fdf-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mantle_(clothing)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-fdf-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-fdf_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-fdf_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-fdf_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Calasibetta, Charlotte Mankey (1988). <i>Fairchild's Dictionary of Fashion</i> (2nd ed.). New York: Fairchild Publications. pp.&#160;363\u201364. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-56367-235-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-56367-235-9\">1-56367-235-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Fairchild%27s+Dictionary+of+Fashion&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pages=363-64&amp;rft.edition=2nd&amp;rft.pub=Fairchild+Publications&amp;rft.date=1988&amp;rft.isbn=1-56367-235-9&amp;rft.aulast=Calasibetta&amp;rft.aufirst=Charlotte+Mankey&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMantle+%28clothing%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span sty